06003nam a22011295i 9781400880607DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162016nju    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)984647720  a97814008806077 a10.1515/97814008806072doi  a(DE-B1597)467887  a(OCoLC)936462919  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aE184.36.P64bB37 2018 7aPOL0030002bisacsh04a973.049242231 aBarnett, Michael N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Star and the Stripes :bA History of the Foreign Policies of American Jews /cMichael N. Barnett. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b12 halftones. 2 line illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. Heine's Law and Jewish Foreign Policies -- tChapter Two. The Making of a Prophetic People (pre-1914) -- tChapter Three. Prophets Mugged by Reality (1914-1945) -- tChapter Four. The Cosmopolitan and the National (1945-1967) -- tChapter Five. The New Tribalism (1967-1990) -- tChapter Six. Back to the Future? (1990-present) -- tChapter Seven. The Foreign Policies of an Uncertain People -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow do American Jews envision their role in the world? Are they tribal-a people whose obligations extend solely to their own? Or are they prophetic-a light unto nations, working to repair the world? The Star and the Stripes is an original, provocative interpretation of the effects of these worldviews on the foreign policy beliefs of American Jews since the nineteenth century. Michael Barnett argues that it all begins with the political identity of American Jews. As Jews, they are committed to their people's survival. As Americans, they identify with, and believe their survival depends on, the American principles of liberalism, religious freedom, and pluralism. This identity and search for inclusion form a political theology of prophetic Judaism that emphasizes the historic mission of Jews to help create a world of peace and justice.The political theology of prophetic Judaism accounts for two enduring features of the foreign policy beliefs of American Jews. They exhibit a cosmopolitan sensibility, advocating on behalf of human rights, humanitarianism, and international law and organizations. They also are suspicious of nationalism-including their own. Contrary to the conventional wisdom that American Jews are natural-born Jewish nationalists, Barnett charts a long history of ambivalence; this ambivalence connects their early rejection of Zionism with the current debate regarding their attachment to Israel. And, Barnett contends, this growing ambivalence also explains the rising popularity of humanitarian and social justice movements among American Jews.Rooted in the understanding of how history shapes a political community's sense of the world, The Star and the Stripes is a bold reading of the past, present, and possible future foreign policies of American Jews.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aJewszUnited StatesxAttitudes. 0aJewszUnited StatesxPolitics and government. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Civics & Citizenship.2bisacsh  a1948.  aAmerican Jewry.  aAmerican Jews.  aAmerican power.  aHolocaust.  aIsrael.  aJewish Problem.  aJewish Question.  aJewish identity.  aJewish state.  aJewishness.  aProphetic Judaism.  aSix-Day War.  aUniversal Declaration of Human Rights.  aZionism.  aacculturation.  aanti-Semitism.  acosmopolitanism.  aforeign policy.  ahuman rights.  ahumanitarianism.  aliberalism.  anationalism.  anon-Orthodox Jew